{"title_page": "Hackensack station (New York, Susquehanna and Western Railroad)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{about|the former [[New York, Susquehanna and Western Railroad|NYSW]] commuter railroad stations in [[Hackensack, New Jersey]]|the [[New Jersey Transit Rail Operations|NJ Transit]] station|Essex Street station (NJ Transit)}}\n{{Infobox station\n | name=Hackensack\n | style=Erie Railroad\n | type=\n | image=NYS&W Alco 236 suburban train, Hackensack, NJ station on September 3, 1965 (24689046542).jpg\n | image_caption=NYS&W suburban train approaching Hackensack, River Street in 1965\n | address= Main Street at Mercer Street<br>[[Hackensack, New Jersey|Hackensack]], [[New Jersey]]\n | coordinates={{coord|40.883879|-74.042820|type:railwaystation_region:US-NJ|display=inline,title}}\n | line= NYS&W Main Line\n | other=\n | structure=\n | platform= 1 side platform\n | depth=\n | levels=\n | tracks= 2\n | passengers=\n | pass_year=\n | pass_percent=\n | pass_system=\n | opened=  {{start date and age|1872}}<ref name =homes/>\n | closed={{start date and age|June 30, 1966}}\n | rebuilt= at River Street<br>September 1949<ref>{{cite news |title=Bids Sought on New Hackensack Station |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29468754/hackensack_river_st_september_29_1949/ |accessdate=March 13, 2019 |work=The Herald-News |date=September 29, 1949 |location=Passaic, New Jersey |page=16|via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref>&ndash;June 29, 1950<ref name=\"1950opening\">{{cite news |title=To Open New RR Station in Hackensack |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29468826/hackensack_station_june_23_1950/ |accessdate=March 13, 2019 |work=The Paterson Evening News |date=June 23, 1950 |page=31|via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref>\n | electrified=Not electrified\n | owned=[[New York, Susquehanna and Western Railroad]]\n | code=1085 (Erie Railroad)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jon-n-bevliles.net/RAILROAD/erie_docs/erie-losn16.html|title=List of Station Names and Numbers|date=May 1, 1916|publisher=[[Erie Railroad]]|location=[[Jersey City, New Jersey]]|accessdate=January 21, 2019}}</ref>\n | services= {{Adjacent stations|system=New York, Susquehanna and Western Railroad|line=Main Line|left=Prospect Avenue|right=Bogota}}\n | mpassengers=\n}}\n\n'''Hackensack''' was a railroad station in [[Hackensack, New Jersey]] on the [[New York, Susquehanna and Western Railway]] Main Line, which provided passenger service between the 1870s and 1960s. The station at Main and Mercer Streets opened in 1872; it was replaced with one at '''River Street''' in 1950.  [[List of Public Service Railway lines|Public Service]] trolley lines served both stations.<ref>{{Citation |last = Eid |first = Joseph F, Jr. & Gummere, Barker|title = Streetcars of New Jersey: Metropolitan Northeast |publisher = \n|year = 2007|url = https://books.google.com/?id=KrbOAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA177&lpg=PA177&dq=hackensack+extension+bergen+traction#v=onepage&q=hackensack%20extension%20bergen%20traction&f=false |isbn = 9780980102628}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:HackensackCBD1905.png|left|thumb|250px|1905 map showing rail and trolley lines and stations in Hackensack]]\nThe Hoboken, Ridgefield and Paterson Railroad was chartered in 1866 to connect Paterson with the [[Port of New York and New Jersey|ports]] along the [[North River (Hudson River)]].<ref name = ICCvaluations>{{Citation   | title = Interstate Commerce Commission Reports: Decisions of the Interstate Commerce Commission of the United States. Valuation reports   | publisher = U.S. Government Printing Office   | year = 1931   | volume = 33}}</ref> The [[New Jersey Midland Railway]] (NJM) was formed in 1870 as a consolidation of several smaller railroads.<ref name = ICCvaluations/> \n \nBy March 1872, the line had been extended west through [[Maywood Station Museum|Maywood]] [[Paterson, New Jersey|Paterson]], [[Wortendyke (NYS&W station)|Wortendyke]], and [[Butler (NYS&W station)|Butler]] to [[Newfoundland (NYS&W station)|Newfoundland]]. It was later extended to Sparta, Newton, Blairstown and across the [[Delaware River]] to [[Stroudsburg, Pennsylvania]]. Soon thereafter, trains running east and south to the [[Hudson Waterfront]] via [[Marion Junction (New Jersey)|Marion Junction]] and the [[Journal Square Transportation Center|Bergen Hill Cut]] to [[Exchange Place station (Pennsylvania Railroad)|Pennsylvania Railroad's depot]] in [[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City]], where transfer was possible to the [[Jersey City Ferry]].<ref name = homes>{{cite journal|last1=Catlin |first1=George L. |title=Homes on the Midland for New York Business Men. |date=1872 |publisher=J. W. Pratt|via = [[HathiTrust]] Digital Library |location=[[New York, New York]]|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=loc.ark:/13960/t7kp8827h;view=1up;seq=1|page=20}}</ref> \n\nThe NJ Midland was absorbed into the New York, Susquehanna and Western Railroad. In 1898, the NYSW became a subsidiary of the [[Erie Railroad]], and made use of Erie's [[Pavonia Terminal]]<ref>{{Citation|last = Mohowski |first = Robert E. |title = The New York, Susquehanna & Western Railroad |publisher = JHU Press |year = 2003 |url = https://books.google.com/?id=c-8VcwgnbOYC&pg=PA49&dq=New+York,+Susquehanna+%26+Western+Railroad+A+Branch+of+the+Erie#v=onepage&q=New%20York%2C%20Susquehanna%20%26%20Western%20Railroad%20A%20Branch%20of%20the%20Erie&f=fals |isbn = 9780801872228 }}</ref> and the [[Pavonia Ferry]] or to [[Susquehanna Transfer station|Susquehanna Transfer]], which provided transfer to buses through the [[Lincoln Tunnel]] to the [[Port Authority Bus Terminal]].\n\nThe station at Main Street was replaced with one at River Street on June 29, 1950.<ref name=\"1950opening\" /> Both were also stops on the [[List of Public Service Railway lines|Public Service]] trolley line.<ref>{{Citation   | last = Eid, Jr.   | first = Joseph   | last2 = Gummere   | first2 = Barker   | title = Streetcars of New Jersey: Metropolitan Northeast   | publisher =    | year = 2007   | url = https://books.google.com/?id=KrbOAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA63&lpg=PA63&dq=Public+service+streetcar+lines#v=onepage&q=Public%20service%20streetcar%20lines&f=false   | isbn = 9780980102628   | quote = }}</ref> There was also a NYSW station in the city at Prospect Avenue. Passenger service on the line was eliminated June 30, 1966; it is now used for exclusively for freight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.klusster.com/klussters/journeys-into-hackensack/publications/hackensack-as-a-long-time-transit-hub-part-3-trains-1277|title=Hackensack as a long-time transit hub - Part 3 - Trains|first=Eric|last=Model|website=Klusster|accessdate=January 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRail service running north-south in Hackensack began in 1865 and was operated by the [[Hackensack and New York Railroad]], which was later reorganized as the [[New Jersey and New York Railroad]] and in 1896 leased by the Erie Railroad,<ref name=\"jones\">{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Wilson E.|title=The Pascack Valley Line - A History of the New Jersey and New York Railroad|publisher=Railroadians of America|year=1996|isbn=0-941652-14-9}}</ref> though there was no interchange with the NYS&W. The [[right of way]] is now [[New Jersey Transit Rail Operations]]'s [[Pascack Valley Line]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.piercehaviland.com/rail/pv.html|title=The Pascack Valley Line|website=www.piercehaviland.com|accessdate=March 14, 2019}}</ref> with stations at [[Essex Street station (NJ Transit)|Essex Street]] and [[Anderson Street station|Anderson Street]].\n\n==Future==\n[[File:Main Street Station NYSW.jpg|thumb|left|Building at Main and Mercer streets in Hackensack along the NYS&W right-of-way, 2015]]\nThe [[Passaic-Bergen Rail Line]] is a project by [[New Jersey Transit]] (NJT) to reintroduce passenger service on a portion of the New York, Susquehanna and Western Railway right-of-way in [[Passaic County, New Jersey|Passaic]] and Bergen counties.<ref name=systra>{{cite web|title=NJ Transit design and engineering services for the Passaic-Bergen Passenger restoration project|publisher=Systra Consulting|url=http://www.systraconsulting.com/expert-services/engineering/infrastructure-.html?systra-project=nj-transit-design-and-engineering-services-for-the-passaic-bergen-passenger-restoration-project-25|accessdate=May 5, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130203173314/http://www.systraconsulting.com/expert-services/engineering/infrastructure-.html?systra-project=nj-transit-design-and-engineering-services-for-the-passaic-bergen-passenger-restoration-project-25|archivedate=February 3, 2013}}</ref>\nA terminal station would be located at State and Mercer Streets, one block west of the NYS&W station. The western terminal would be at [[Hawthorne station (NJ Transit)|Hawthorne]].\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Template:NYSW (passenger 1939-1966) map|NYSW (passenger 1939-1966) map]]\n* [[Operating Passenger Railroad Stations Thematic Resource (New Jersey)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.njtpa.org/getmedia/38517273-2e3a-4ee4-be14-5604191e2320/TCSP-Hackensack-FINAL-Web.pdf.aspx Hackensack TOD Report 2013]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hackensack (NYS&W)}}\n[[Category:Hackensack, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Bergen County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Former New York, Susquehanna and Western Railway stations|Hackensack station]]\n[[Category:Defunct railway stations in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1966]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the former [[New York, Susquehanna and Western Railroad|NYSW]] commuter railroad stations in [[Hackensack, New Jersey]]|the [[New Jersey Transit Rail Operations|NJ Transit]] station|Essex Street station (NJ Transit)}}\n{{Infobox station\n | name=Hackensack\n | style=Erie Railroad\n | type=\n | image=NYS&W Alco 236 suburban train, Hackensack, NJ station on September 3, 1965 (24689046542).jpg\n | image_caption=NYS&W suburban train approaching Hackensack, River Street in 1965\n | address= Main Street at Mercer Street<br>[[Hackensack, New Jersey|Hackensack]], [[New Jersey]]\n | coordinates={{coord|40.883879|-74.042820|type:railwaystation_region:US-NJ|display=inline,title}}\n | line= NYS&W Main Line\n | other=\n | structure=\n | platform= 1 side platform\n | depth=\n | levels=\n | tracks= 2\n | passengers=\n | pass_year=\n | pass_percent=\n | pass_system=\n | opened=  {{start date and age|1872}}<ref name =homes/>\n | closed={{start date and age|June 30, 1966}}\n | rebuilt= at River Street<br>September&nbsp;1949<ref>{{cite news |title=Bids Sought on New Hackensack Station |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29468754/hackensack_river_st_september_29_1949/ |accessdate=March 13, 2019 |work=The Herald-News |date=September 29, 1949 |location=Passaic, New Jersey |page=16|via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref>&ndash;June 29, 1950<ref name=\"1950opening\">{{cite news |title=To Open New RR Station in Hackensack |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/29468826/hackensack_station_june_23_1950/ |accessdate=March 13, 2019 |work=The Paterson Evening News |date=June 23, 1950 |page=31|via=Newspapers.com}} {{open access}}</ref>\n | electrified=Not electrified\n | owned=[[New York, Susquehanna and Western Railroad]]\n | code=1085 (Erie Railroad)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jon-n-bevliles.net/RAILROAD/erie_docs/erie-losn16.html|title=List of Station Names and Numbers|date=May 1, 1916|publisher=[[Erie Railroad]]|location=[[Jersey City, New Jersey]]|accessdate=January 21, 2019}}</ref>\n | services= {{Adjacent stations|system=New York, Susquehanna and Western Railroad|line=Main Line|left=Prospect Avenue|right=Bogota}}\n | mpassengers=\n}}\n\n'''Hackensack''' was a railroad station in [[Hackensack, New Jersey]] on the [[New York, Susquehanna and Western Railway]] Main Line, which provided passenger service between the 1870s and 1960s. The station at Main and Mercer Streets opened in 1872; it was replaced with one at '''River Street''' in 1950.  [[List of Public Service Railway lines|Public Service]] trolley lines served both stations.<ref>{{Citation |last = Eid |first = Joseph F, Jr. & Gummere, Barker|title = Streetcars of New Jersey: Metropolitan Northeast |publisher = \n|year = 2007|url = https://books.google.com/?id=KrbOAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA177&lpg=PA177&dq=hackensack+extension+bergen+traction#v=onepage&q=hackensack%20extension%20bergen%20traction&f=false |isbn = 9780980102628}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:HackensackCBD1905.png|left|thumb|250px|1905 map showing rail and trolley lines and stations in Hackensack]]\nThe Hoboken, Ridgefield and Paterson Railroad was chartered in 1866 to connect Paterson with the [[Port of New York and New Jersey|ports]] along the [[North River (Hudson River)]].<ref name = ICCvaluations>{{Citation   | title = Interstate Commerce Commission Reports: Decisions of the Interstate Commerce Commission of the United States. Valuation reports   | publisher = U.S. Government Printing Office   | year = 1931   | volume = 33}}</ref> The [[New Jersey Midland Railway]] (NJM) was formed in 1870 as a consolidation of several smaller railroads.<ref name = ICCvaluations/> \n \nBy March 1872, the line had been extended west through [[Maywood Station Museum|Maywood]] [[Paterson, New Jersey|Paterson]], [[Wortendyke (NYS&W station)|Wortendyke]], and [[Butler (NYS&W station)|Butler]] to [[Newfoundland (NYS&W station)|Newfoundland]]. It was later extended to Sparta, Newton, Blairstown and across the [[Delaware River]] to [[Stroudsburg, Pennsylvania]]. Soon thereafter, trains running east and south to the [[Hudson Waterfront]] via [[Marion Junction (New Jersey)|Marion Junction]] and the [[Journal Square Transportation Center|Bergen Hill Cut]] to [[Exchange Place station (Pennsylvania Railroad)|Pennsylvania Railroad's depot]] in [[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City]], where transfer was possible to the [[Jersey City Ferry]].<ref name = homes>{{cite journal|last1=Catlin |first1=George L. |title=Homes on the Midland for New York Business Men. |date=1872 |publisher=J. W. Pratt|via = [[HathiTrust]] Digital Library |location=[[New York, New York]]|url=https://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=loc.ark:/13960/t7kp8827h;view=1up;seq=1|page=20}}</ref> \n\nThe NJ Midland was absorbed into the New York, Susquehanna and Western Railroad. In 1898, the NYSW became a subsidiary of the [[Erie Railroad]], and made use of Erie's [[Pavonia Terminal]]<ref>{{Citation|last = Mohowski |first = Robert E. |title = The New York, Susquehanna & Western Railroad |publisher = JHU Press |year = 2003 |url = https://books.google.com/?id=c-8VcwgnbOYC&pg=PA49&dq=New+York,+Susquehanna+%26+Western+Railroad+A+Branch+of+the+Erie#v=onepage&q=New%20York%2C%20Susquehanna%20%26%20Western%20Railroad%20A%20Branch%20of%20the%20Erie&f=fals |isbn = 9780801872228 }}</ref> and the [[Pavonia Ferry]] or to [[Susquehanna Transfer station|Susquehanna Transfer]], which provided transfer to buses through the [[Lincoln Tunnel]] to the [[Port Authority Bus Terminal]].\n\nThe station at Main Street was replaced with one at River Street on June 29, 1950.<ref name=\"1950opening\" /> Both were also stops on the [[List of Public Service Railway lines|Public Service]] trolley line.<ref>{{Citation   | last = Eid, Jr.   | first = Joseph   | last2 = Gummere   | first2 = Barker   | title = Streetcars of New Jersey: Metropolitan Northeast   | publisher =    | year = 2007   | url = https://books.google.com/?id=KrbOAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA63&lpg=PA63&dq=Public+service+streetcar+lines#v=onepage&q=Public%20service%20streetcar%20lines&f=false   | isbn = 9780980102628   | quote = }}</ref> There was also a NYSW station in the city at Prospect Avenue. Passenger service on the line was eliminated June 30, 1966; it is now used for exclusively for freight.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.klusster.com/klussters/journeys-into-hackensack/publications/hackensack-as-a-long-time-transit-hub-part-3-trains-1277|title=Hackensack as a long-time transit hub - Part 3 - Trains|first=Eric|last=Model|website=Klusster|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nRail service running north-south in Hackensack began in 1865 and was operated by the [[Hackensack and New York Railroad]], which was later reorganized as the [[New Jersey and New York Railroad]] and in 1896 leased by the Erie Railroad,<ref name=\"jones\">{{cite book|last=Jones|first=Wilson E.|title=The Pascack Valley Line - A History of the New Jersey and New York Railroad|publisher=Railroadians of America|year=1996|isbn=0-941652-14-9}}</ref> though there was no interchange with the NYS&W. The [[right of way]] is now [[New Jersey Transit Rail Operations]]'s [[Pascack Valley Line]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.piercehaviland.com/rail/pv.html|title=The Pascack Valley Line|website=www.piercehaviland.com|accessdate=14 March 2019}}</ref> with stations at [[Essex Street station (NJ Transit)|Essex Street]] and [[Anderson Street station|Anderson Street]].\n\n==Future==\n[[File:Main Street Station NYSW.jpg|thumb|left|Building at Main and Mercer streets in Hackensack along the NYS&W right-of-way, 2015]]\nThe [[Passaic-Bergen Rail Line]] is a project by [[New Jersey Transit]] (NJT) to reintroduce passenger service on a portion of the New York, Susquehanna and Western Railway right-of-way in [[Passaic County, New Jersey|Passaic]] and Bergen counties.<ref name=systra>{{cite web|title=NJ Transit design and engineering services for the Passaic-Bergen Passenger restoration project|publisher=Systra Consulting|url=http://www.systraconsulting.com/expert-services/engineering/infrastructure-.html?systra-project=nj-transit-design-and-engineering-services-for-the-passaic-bergen-passenger-restoration-project-25|accessdate=May 5, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130203173314/http://www.systraconsulting.com/expert-services/engineering/infrastructure-.html?systra-project=nj-transit-design-and-engineering-services-for-the-passaic-bergen-passenger-restoration-project-25|archivedate=February 3, 2013|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\nA terminal station would be located at State and Mercer Streets, one block west of the NYS&W station. The western terminal would be at [[Hawthorne station (NJ Transit)|Hawthorne]].\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Template:NYSW (passenger 1939-1966) map|NYSW (passenger 1939-1966) map]]\n* [[Operating Passenger Railroad Stations Thematic Resource (New Jersey)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.njtpa.org/getmedia/38517273-2e3a-4ee4-be14-5604191e2320/TCSP-Hackensack-FINAL-Web.pdf.aspx Hackensack TOD Report 2013]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hackensack (NYS&W)}}\n[[Category:Hackensack, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Railway stations in Bergen County, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Former New York, Susquehanna and Western Railway stations|Hackensack station]]\n[[Category:Defunct railway stations in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1966]]\n", "name_user": "Kew Gardens 613", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hackensack_station_(New_York,_Susquehanna_and_Western_Railroad)"}
{"title_page": "The Water Cure", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|1916 film}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Water Cure\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| director       = Will Louis\n| producer       = Louis Burstein\n| writer         =\n| starring       = [[Oliver Hardy]]\n| cinematography =\n| editing        =\n| distributor    =\n| released       = {{Film date|1916|05|11}}\n| runtime        =\n| country        = United States\n| language       = Silent film<br>English intertitles\n| budget         =\n}}\n\n'''''The Water Cure''''' is a 1916 American [[silent film|silent]] [[comedy film]] featuring [[Oliver Hardy]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=jLS9ht9bWPkC&pg=PA206&dq=%22The+Water+Cure%22+Oliver+Hardy#v=onepage|title=What Was The Film When? The Movies of Laurel and Hardy|first1=Mark|last1=Potts|first2=Dave|last2=Shephard|date=March 23, 2019|publisher=Lulu|isbn=9780955531835|accessdate=March 23, 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=dIs_DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT71&dq=%22The+Water+Cure%22+Oliver+Hardy#v=onepage|title=Another Fine Mess - The Laurel & Hardy Story|first=Raymond Valinoti|last=Jr|publisher=BearManor Media|accessdate=March 23, 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Oliver Hardy]] - Plump (as Babe Hardy)\n* Billy Ruge - Runt\n* Elsie MacLeod\n* Florence McLaughlin\n* Edna Reynolds\n* Bert Tracy\n* Joe Cohen\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1916]]\n* [[Oliver Hardy filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0007540|title=The Water Cure}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Water Cure, The}}\n[[Category:1916 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:1910s short films]]\n[[Category:American silent short films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:1910s comedy films]]\n[[Category:American comedy films]]\n[[Category:comedy short films]]\n{{1910s-short-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1916 film}}\n{{other uses}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Water Cure\n| image          =\n| caption        =\n| director       = Will Louis\n| producer       = Louis Burstein\n| writer         =\n| starring       = [[Oliver Hardy]]\n| cinematography =\n| editing        =\n| distributor    =\n| released       = {{Film date|1916|05|11}}\n| runtime        =\n| country        = United States\n| language       = Silent film<br>English intertitles\n| budget         =\n}}\n\n'''''The Water Cure''''' is a 1916 American [[silent film|silent]] [[comedy film]] featuring [[Oliver Hardy]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=jLS9ht9bWPkC&pg=PA206&dq=%22The+Water+Cure%22+Oliver+Hardy#v=onepage|title=What Was The Film When? The Movies of Laurel and Hardy|first1=Mark|last1=Potts|first2=Dave|last2=Shephard|date=23 March 2019|publisher=Lulu|isbn=9780955531835|accessdate=23 March 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/?id=dIs_DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT71&dq=%22The+Water+Cure%22+Oliver+Hardy#v=onepage|title=Another Fine Mess - The Laurel & Hardy Story|first=Raymond Valinoti|last=Jr|publisher=BearManor Media|accessdate=23 March 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Oliver Hardy]] - Plump (as Babe Hardy)\n* Billy Ruge - Runt\n* Elsie MacLeod\n* Florence McLaughlin\n* Edna Reynolds\n* Bert Tracy\n* Joe Cohen\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of American films of 1916]]\n* [[Oliver Hardy filmography]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0007540|title=The Water Cure}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Water Cure, The}}\n[[Category:1916 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:1910s short films]]\n[[Category:American silent short films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:1910s comedy films]]\n[[Category:American comedy films]]\n[[Category:comedy short films]]\n{{1910s-short-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page":